es us to reach beyond the limits of everyday life and forge virtual relationships and imagined communities. Although Maurice Blanchot wrote of the impossibility of writing, the passion and paradox of literature lies in its attempt to achieve the impossible--a leap of faith that calls to mind the mystic's dark night of the soul, unrequited love, nostalgic or utopian longing, and the ethnographer's attempt to know the world from the standpoint of others, to put himself or herself in their place. Every writer, whether of ethnography, poetry, or fiction, imagines that his or her own experiences echo the experiences of others, and that despite the need for isolation and silence his or her work consummates a relationship with them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAmerican fictionxHistory and criticismy20th century. 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAuthorship. 0aEnglish languagexWriting. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  aart.  aartists.  aauthors.  adark night of the soul.  aempathy.  aengaging.  aethnographer.  aethnography.  afiction writers.  aimagination.  aimpossibility of writing.  aleap of faith.  alife experiences.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary.  aliterature.  alively.  alonging.  amagic.  ameditation.  amodes of understanding.  amodes of writing.  amodes.  anostalgia.  aoral storytelling.  apoet.  apoetry.  arelationship.  aritual.  asocial science.  astudents and teachers.  aunrequited love.  autopia.  aworldliness.  awriting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027526340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095482340uhttps://w